漏洞描述

fastjson采用黑白名单的方法来防御反序列化漏洞，导致当黑客不断发掘新的反序列化Gadgets类时，在autoType关闭的情况下仍然可能可以绕过黑白名单防御机制，造成远程命令执行漏洞。经研究，该漏洞利用门槛较低，可绕过autoType限制，风险影响较大。阿里云应急响应中心提醒fastjson用户尽快采取安全措施阻止漏洞攻击。

影响版本

fastjson <=1.2.68

fastjson sec版本 <= sec9

安全版本

fastjson >=1.2.69

Take the library based approach for clustering. End-user clustering pass must provide a specific clustering policies to the generic API.

1. Values constraints propagation and refinement is not properly supported yet.
2. A lot of inefficient linear lookups that will be removed once proper constraints propagation is implemented, and it will become clear what auxiliary data structures are required.

tf_to_corert still relies on the generic cluster_ops_by_policy_pass.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 372330771
Change-Id: I5cc3a70776c51e629f35d92ac3eba1e1f88c0d5d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dwyatte/tensorflow/commits/c6f71c50db479cdaaa55cbfdd66ba41a77c86b9a"},{"sha":"05963dfc0aea5f8b26f0f85a84787b3f4f771db0","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Fix catastrophic cancellation in Jacobi eigendecomposition convergence test.

Computing the off_diag_norm as (frobenius_norm - diag_norm) suffers from cancellation problems when we get close to convergence. Instead, compute the off-diagonal norm directly.

Raise the default tolerance to 1e-5 to avoid regressing performance. This is a reasonable thing to do since we are now actually enforcing the tolerance a bit better; previously everything cancelled to zero when we got close to such a small tolerance value.

Also update the XLA:Python bindings to use the same tol/max_iters defaults as the C++ API.

Change-Id: Ice2e722179b46090d28a26fb1d3346bfcc131ebf","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dwyatte/tensorflow/commits/42fb47a60cd5d88321781e366d768e88c61ac7b4"},{"sha":"1bebe43aef5d89618b717a8c36f660a10e12582c","author":{"name":"Feng Liu","email":"3f098ac60ccdd3d0addfa2e58b2df0bb47e6eba5@google.com"},"message":"Add quantization related TFR built-in ops

Four TFR built-in ops are added to write quantization related composition.

"tfr.quant_raw_data" and "tfr.quant_qparam" are added to handle the quantized
type of the input tensors.

"tfr.quant_rescale" is added since the specific implementation depends on the
platform, i.e. floating-point rescale or integer shiftt/multiple. With this
abstraction, we can legalize it to the platform specific operations later on.

"tfr.quant_act_range" is added to simplify the composition implementation. This
can also be modeled as a new composite op.

[{"sha":"3e2165a526f74cead337550f15ed9621b2a55455","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Fix the elemental emitter for `add` on `pred`.

Previously it would emit integer addition instructions on the `i8`
representation of a `pred`, which resulted in out-of-range values that caused
havoc in various places (e.g. made `Literal::ToString` print `pred[]
tru\0\0Ca)`, and made `not` fail to actually negate the result).  Now it emits
a bitwise or instruction instead, which maps in-range values to in-range
values.

This also comes with equivalent transformations for other permitted arithmetic
ops on `pred`, which were not incorrect, but needlessly expensive.

This fixes the immediate miscompile on the linked bug (and
https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5406), but since that bug revealed other
inconsistencies with MLIR conversions, it's not yet marked as fixed.

Signed-off-by: Yong Tang <yong.tang.github@outlook.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yongtang/tensorflow/commits/7ac8b36d83616ace8d23f64fd66462a36ca008c3"},{"sha":"7faa27fdfa3be62cb506585083811fccbfc5cc79","author":{"name":"Yong Tang","email":"765086fe2e0c1f980161f127fec596800f327f62@outlook.com"},"message":"Remove duplicated `Env::Default` to fix gcs issue on Windows

This PR tries to address the issue raised in 49515 where
gcs is not available through tf.io.gfile.GFile interface.

The reason was that on Windows -config=monolithic was used
in bazel which includes multiple copies of `Env::Default`

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Fix the elemental emitter for `add` on `pred`.

Previously it would emit integer addition instructions on the `i8`
representation of a `pred`, which resulted in out-of-range values that caused
havoc in various places (e.g. made `Literal::ToString` print `pred[]
tru\0\0Ca)`, and made `not` fail to actually negate the result).  Now it emits
a bitwise or instruction instead, which maps in-range values to in-range
values.

This also comes with equivalent transformations for other permitted arithmetic
ops on `pred`, which were not incorrect, but needlessly expensive.

This fixes the immediate miscompile on the linked bug (and
https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5406), but since that bug revealed other
inconsistencies with MLIR conversions, it's not yet marked as fixed.

[{"sha":"f0f51ce06f032f7e5a7bfbbdcc28f608d5199e47","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Extend scalar broadcast optimization for ConstOp to all types

ConstOp xla op kernel avoids creation of large tensors if the proto representation has only one element. This encodes tensors that have the same value repeated for all the elements. This was limited to only some of the types supported by XLA.

This change extends the above optimization to all the primitive types supported by XLA.

Added a distribution strategy test as we want to feed the full program to XLA in the test to make sure the large tensor is not materialized anywhere.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Fix the elemental emitter for `add` on `pred`.

Previously it would emit integer addition instructions on the `i8`
representation of a `pred`, which resulted in out-of-range values that caused
havoc in various places (e.g. made `Literal::ToString` print `pred[]
tru\0\0Ca)`, and made `not` fail to actually negate the result).  Now it emits
a bitwise or instruction instead, which maps in-range values to in-range
values.

This also comes with equivalent transformations for other permitted arithmetic
ops on `pred`, which were not incorrect, but needlessly expensive.

This fixes the immediate miscompile on the linked bug (and
https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5406), but since that bug revealed other
inconsistencies with MLIR conversions, it's not yet marked as fixed.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Fix the elemental emitter for `add` on `pred`.

Previously it would emit integer addition instructions on the `i8`
representation of a `pred`, which resulted in out-of-range values that caused
havoc in various places (e.g. made `Literal::ToString` print `pred[]
tru\0\0Ca)`, and made `not` fail to actually negate the result).  Now it emits
a bitwise or instruction instead, which maps in-range values to in-range
values.

This also comes with equivalent transformations for other permitted arithmetic
ops on `pred`, which were not incorrect, but needlessly expensive.

This fixes the immediate miscompile on the linked bug (and
https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5406), but since that bug revealed other
inconsistencies with MLIR conversions, it's not yet marked as fixed.

Change-Id: Idbb3133b21927cd7a605369e7fa0d6fa3d050348","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/854d04a464d18af38a160b53e90b0279f905eaaa"},{"sha":"f0f51ce06f032f7e5a7bfbbdcc28f608d5199e47","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Extend scalar broadcast optimization for ConstOp to all types

ConstOp xla op kernel avoids creation of large tensors if the proto representation has only one element. This encodes tensors that have the same value repeated for all the elements. This was limited to only some of the types supported by XLA.

This change extends the above optimization to all the primitive types supported by XLA.

Added a distribution strategy test as we want to feed the full program to XLA in the test to make sure the large tensor is not materialized anywhere.

Change-Id: I5cc3a70776c51e629f35d92ac3eba1e1f88c0d5d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/burgerkingeater/tensorflow/commits/c6f71c50db479cdaaa55cbfdd66ba41a77c86b9a"},{"sha":"05963dfc0aea5f8b26f0f85a84787b3f4f771db0","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Fix catastrophic cancellation in Jacobi eigendecomposition convergence test.

Computing the off_diag_norm as (frobenius_norm - diag_norm) suffers from cancellation problems when we get close to convergence. Instead, compute the off-diagonal norm directly.

Raise the default tolerance to 1e-5 to avoid regressing performance. This is a reasonable thing to do since we are now actually enforcing the tolerance a bit better; previously everything cancelled to zero when we got close to such a small tolerance value.

Also update the XLA:Python bindings to use the same tol/max_iters defaults as the C++ API.

Change-Id: Ice2e722179b46090d28a26fb1d3346bfcc131ebf","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/burgerkingeater/tensorflow/commits/42fb47a60cd5d88321781e366d768e88c61ac7b4"},{"sha":"1bebe43aef5d89618b717a8c36f660a10e12582c","author":{"name":"Feng Liu","email":"3f098ac60ccdd3d0addfa2e58b2df0bb47e6eba5@google.com"},"message":"Add quantization related TFR built-in ops

Four TFR built-in ops are added to write quantization related composition.

"tfr.quant_raw_data" and "tfr.quant_qparam" are added to handle the quantized
type of the input tensors.

"tfr.quant_rescale" is added since the specific implementation depends on the
platform, i.e. floating-point rescale or integer shiftt/multiple. With this
abstraction, we can legalize it to the platform specific operations later on.

"tfr.quant_act_range" is added to simplify the composition implementation. This
can also be modeled as a new composite op.

leads to resource exhaustion for `std::complex` solves (`Internal: too many
resources requested for launch`) due to an insufficient number of registers
per thread.

Adjusting the configuration to account for kernel resources fixes this.

This patch provide a toolchain file that allows to build the library
for baremetal applications. Minimal changes have been applied to the
code to be able to compile with a baremetal toolchain.

The option `CV_BAREMETAL` is used to guard the bits in the code that
are baremetal-specific.

The toolchain file requires the path to the baremetal
toolchain. Example cmake invocation:

    cmake ../opencv/ \
      -DCMAKE_TOOLCHAIN_FILE=../opencv/platforms/baremetal/aarch64.toolchain.cmake \
      -DBAREMETAL_TOOLCHAIN_PATH=/absolute/path/to/gcc-baremetal-toolchain/bin/ \
      -DBUILD_EXAMPLES=ON

A barematel toolchain for targeting aarch64 can be found at [1], under
`aarch64-none-elf`.

[1] https://developer.arm.com/tools-and-software/open-source-software/developer-tools/gnu-toolchain/gnu-a/downloads

The folder `samples/baremetal` provides two example baremetal
applications.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/fpetrogalli/opencv/commits/3ad56858ded4d1c4347af27314683f3f51b8f6ea"},{"sha":"90d5f9d562f08b78312e5e95447a00b265800b68","author":{"name":"Francesco Petrogalli","email":"743152b921210732b2796f9fe9db99ef50b10ebc@arm.com"},"message":"Disable threads in openjpeg from the toolchain file.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/fpetrogalli/opencv/commits/90d5f9d562f08b78312e5e95447a00b265800b68"}]

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Fix the elemental emitter for `add` on `pred`.

Previously it would emit integer addition instructions on the `i8`
representation of a `pred`, which resulted in out-of-range values that caused
havoc in various places (e.g. made `Literal::ToString` print `pred[]
tru\0\0Ca)`, and made `not` fail to actually negate the result).  Now it emits
a bitwise or instruction instead, which maps in-range values to in-range
values.

This also comes with equivalent transformations for other permitted arithmetic
ops on `pred`, which were not incorrect, but needlessly expensive.

This fixes the immediate miscompile on the linked bug (and
https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5406), but since that bug revealed other
inconsistencies with MLIR conversions, it's not yet marked as fixed.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Fix the elemental emitter for `add` on `pred`.

Previously it would emit integer addition instructions on the `i8`
representation of a `pred`, which resulted in out-of-range values that caused
havoc in various places (e.g. made `Literal::ToString` print `pred[]
tru\0\0Ca)`, and made `not` fail to actually negate the result).  Now it emits
a bitwise or instruction instead, which maps in-range values to in-range
values.

This also comes with equivalent transformations for other permitted arithmetic
ops on `pred`, which were not incorrect, but needlessly expensive.

This fixes the immediate miscompile on the linked bug (and
https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5406), but since that bug revealed other
inconsistencies with MLIR conversions, it's not yet marked as fixed.

Change-Id: Idbb3133b21927cd7a605369e7fa0d6fa3d050348","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Geolem/tensorflow/commits/854d04a464d18af38a160b53e90b0279f905eaaa"},{"sha":"f0f51ce06f032f7e5a7bfbbdcc28f608d5199e47","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Extend scalar broadcast optimization for ConstOp to all types

ConstOp xla op kernel avoids creation of large tensors if the proto representation has only one element. This encodes tensors that have the same value repeated for all the elements. This was limited to only some of the types supported by XLA.

This change extends the above optimization to all the primitive types supported by XLA.

Added a distribution strategy test as we want to feed the full program to XLA in the test to make sure the large tensor is not materialized anywhere.

problematic since daemon logs can grow rapidly, potentially exhausting disk
space.

to be written. By default, this limit is 333 entries per second max.

Change-Id: I26bf93b00f131b39e260cd2391d8cc6b0a1be51d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/GulajavaMinistudio/tensorflow/commits/12ef86acfaf252e3470a0b32d126a03d1dc3f432"},{"sha":"5177e09c9f302372137f28ab7798a8a413c352f7","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Compare tensor bytes and proto representation for tensors with large expansion

This moves the generally applicable short circuit logic from FastAreTensorProtosEqual to AreTensorProtosEqual and only compares proto for large values if false positives are allowed.

I expect the short circuit logic to be beneficial in general given the prevalence for splat tensor attributes. This logic may have some overhead for tiny tensors in computation of number of elements twice. For tensors with large expansion, additional proto comparison should be cheaper compared to proto construction and then serialized string comparison.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Fix the elemental emitter for `add` on `pred`.

Previously it would emit integer addition instructions on the `i8`
representation of a `pred`, which resulted in out-of-range values that caused
havoc in various places (e.g. made `Literal::ToString` print `pred[]
tru\0\0Ca)`, and made `not` fail to actually negate the result).  Now it emits
a bitwise or instruction instead, which maps in-range values to in-range
values.

This also comes with equivalent transformations for other permitted arithmetic
ops on `pred`, which were not incorrect, but needlessly expensive.

This fixes the immediate miscompile on the linked bug (and
https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5406), but since that bug revealed other
inconsistencies with MLIR conversions, it's not yet marked as fixed.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Fix the elemental emitter for `add` on `pred`.

Previously it would emit integer addition instructions on the `i8`
representation of a `pred`, which resulted in out-of-range values that caused
havoc in various places (e.g. made `Literal::ToString` print `pred[]
tru\0\0Ca)`, and made `not` fail to actually negate the result).  Now it emits
a bitwise or instruction instead, which maps in-range values to in-range
values.

This also comes with equivalent transformations for other permitted arithmetic
ops on `pred`, which were not incorrect, but needlessly expensive.

This fixes the immediate miscompile on the linked bug (and
https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5406), but since that bug revealed other
inconsistencies with MLIR conversions, it's not yet marked as fixed.

Change-Id: Idbb3133b21927cd7a605369e7fa0d6fa3d050348","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/854d04a464d18af38a160b53e90b0279f905eaaa"},{"sha":"f0f51ce06f032f7e5a7bfbbdcc28f608d5199e47","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Extend scalar broadcast optimization for ConstOp to all types

ConstOp xla op kernel avoids creation of large tensors if the proto representation has only one element. This encodes tensors that have the same value repeated for all the elements. This was limited to only some of the types supported by XLA.

This change extends the above optimization to all the primitive types supported by XLA.

Added a distribution strategy test as we want to feed the full program to XLA in the test to make sure the large tensor is not materialized anywhere.

Logging to daemon logs every time there's an error with a log driver can be
problematic since daemon logs can grow rapidly, potentially exhausting disk
space.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Make handling of singular matrices consistent for CPU, GPU, and XLA in linalg.tridiagonal_solve. Previously, the op would abort when encountering a singular matrix and return an error on CPU. On GPU it would only do so for n == 1 and n == 2, but return an undefined result for n > 2.

This change alters the behavior such that the op does not abort, but returns all non-finite values (NaN or +/-Inf) for singular matrices. This is also more consistent with the behavior when the program uses XLA, which is generally not able to abort in the middle of a computation.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Fix the elemental emitter for `add` on `pred`.

Previously it would emit integer addition instructions on the `i8`
representation of a `pred`, which resulted in out-of-range values that caused
havoc in various places (e.g. made `Literal::ToString` print `pred[]
tru\0\0Ca)`, and made `not` fail to actually negate the result).  Now it emits
a bitwise or instruction instead, which maps in-range values to in-range
values.

This also comes with equivalent transformations for other permitted arithmetic
ops on `pred`, which were not incorrect, but needlessly expensive.

This fixes the immediate miscompile on the linked bug (and
https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5406), but since that bug revealed other
inconsistencies with MLIR conversions, it's not yet marked as fixed.
